ou go beyond analytics and improve your product experience with user insigh=
ts, delivered fast. The world=E2=80=99s best product teams including the te=
ams at Notion, Loom, and Robinhood use Sprig=E2=80=99s in-app surveys and c=
oncept and usability tests to capture insights from their users and build b=
etter products.
Sprig [ https://substack.com/redirect/313dad75-3c69-4d5c-bb81-ba653d00c06c?=
j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] means =
you can do more with less and there=E2=80=99s a plan for every product. Pri=
cing [ https://substack.com/redirect/313dad75-3c69-4d5c-bb81-ba653d00c06c?j=
=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] starts =
at just $175/month and allows you to run two in-product surveys and two con=
cept tests every month.
Every week, at the bottom of the newsletter, I use a Sprig survey to collec=
t insights from you -- you click a button to tell me whether you loved or h=
ated the newsletter and write a comment, and Sprig categorizes responses wi=
th machine learning so that I can get a quick pulse check.=C2=A0=C2=A0
Here=E2=80=99s what I love about Sprig [ https://substack.com/redirect/313d=
ad75-3c69-4d5c-bb81-ba653d00c06c?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZj=
mlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]:
The UX is clean and simple, consumer-grade, and they have 75 templates whic=
h makes getting started so easy
It=E2=80=99s incredibly fast to source participants and launch a survey or =
concept test
As a dashboard junkie, I love watching the results and AI-driven insights r=
oll in in real-time, even, and especially, when the feedback is harsh!
We actually almost stopped publishing this newsletter after edition #11 unt=
il we ran a Sprig Survey and discovered that 95% of you enjoyed reading it=
=E2=80=A6so you can thank Sprig for the Weekly Dose of Optimism!
(1) What's Our Problem?: A Self-Help Book for Societies [ https://substack.=
com/redirect/73ad31dd-019f-4f4d-9e05-bdbbf28566fc?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb=
8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
A review of Tim Urban=E2=80=99s (Wait But Why) forthcoming book
Packy here. If you=E2=80=99ve been reading Not Boring for a while, you know=
 how much I love Tim Urban=E2=80=99s work. I based my Fount essay [ https:/=
/substack.com/redirect/5274328d-ee07-4496-b06c-0c2bbd211537?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXA=
wZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] on his Neuralink piec=
e [ https://substack.com/redirect/9b95f216-0af8-4437-89d7-977ae5645fee?j=3D=
eyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]. The secon=
d sentence in my piece was: =E2=80=9CNo one alive is better at explaining t=
echnology, humans, or Elon than Wait But Why [ https://substack.com/redirec=
t/9689abe6-e689-4c93-9aaf-bcebc60da21b?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_Zl=
NuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]=E2=80=99s Tim Urban [ https://substack.com=
/redirect/519008d8-14c0-40e5-baa5-9c4074e05594?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5=
T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ].=E2=80=9D=20
So it was a career highlight when Tim sent me a pre-print of his new book, =
What=E2=80=99s Our Problem? [ https://substack.com/redirect/73ad31dd-019f-4=
f4d-9e05-bdbbf28566fc?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOs=
a8-6m8ExkRNpU ] earlier this week. (I=E2=80=99d already pre-ordered it. It =
comes out Tuesday.)
I=E2=80=99ve been ripping through it over the past couple of days and am ab=
out halfway through. It=E2=80=99s even better than I expected.=20
If human history is a 1,000 page book, each page covering 250 years, we=E2=
=80=99re turning to page 1,001, which excites and scares Tim because of thr=
ee facts:
Technology is exponential.
More technology means higher stakes.
My society is currently acting like a poopy-pantsed four-year-old who dropp=
ed its ice cream.
We talk a lot about exponential technology in Not Boring and I=E2=80=99m ob=
viously optimistic about all the good things that technology will help peop=
le achieve, but there=E2=80=99s a real risk that we fumble the opportunity.=
 One of the saddest facts about the current state of affairs is that, =E2=
=80=9CEverything is amazing and nobody is happy. [ https://substack.com/red=
irect/bf9de520-e73e-4ced-944d-5b5c44190343?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7Gn=
A_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]=E2=80=9D It=E2=80=99s gotten worse sin=
ce Louis CK said that on Conan 13 years ago, and What=E2=80=99s Our Problem=
? examines why that is, how we got here, and what to do about it.=20
Our problem, according to the book, is that hypercharged tribalism is winni=
ng out over the search for truth. Tim is willing to piss off people on both=
 sides by calling out the =E2=80=9Clow-rung=E2=80=9D thinking that dominate=
s both parties =E2=80=94 Trump Republicans and Social Justice Fundamentalis=
ts =E2=80=94 in order to defend the quest for truth and liberal ideals.=20
David Deutsch=E2=80=99s Principle of Optimism states that =E2=80=9CAll evil=
s are caused by insufficient knowledge.=E2=80=9D In order to cure those evi=
ls, we need to get back to a society that prioritizes truth over tribe. It=
=E2=80=99s going to be difficult to get out of this rut, but naming the pro=
blem and explaining it in a way that anyone can understand is an important =
first step.=20
Reading What=E2=80=99s Our Problem? has made me more optimistic that we can=
 get out of this mess if enough people snap out of and push back on the bas=
e tribalism that=E2=80=99s taken over. It=E2=80=99s certainly made me rethi=
nk my own positions. Unless something goes horribly wrong in the back half =
of the book, I can safely make this claim:
America will be a better country if everyone reads this book. =F0=9F=87=BA=
=F0=9F=87=B8=20
More pre-orders means it will shoot to the top of more lists, which means m=
ore people will read it. Do your part. Order it. [ https://substack.com/red=
irect/73ad31dd-019f-4f4d-9e05-bdbbf28566fc?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7Gn=
A_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]=20
(2) How a pioneering diabetes drug offers hope for preventing autoimmune di=
sorders [ https://substack.com/redirect/39616095-7b5b-4a8d-a9fe-03fb0b085b2=
8?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Elie Dolgin [ https://substack.com/redirect/fc481352-6fca-4fb3-ad29-5d416fd=
4a500?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] =
for Nature=20
Teplizumab is a type of antibody therapy. It blocks T cells, the =E2=80=99a=
ttack dogs=E2=80=99 of the immune system, stopping them destroying insulin-=
producing islet cells in the pancreas. It=E2=80=99s also the first drug pro=
ven to delay the onset of an autoimmune disorder. And its development provi=
des a roadmap for the discovery of pharmaceuticals to stall or prevent othe=
r conditions, including rheumatoid arthritis and multiple sclerosis.
The effectiveness of Teplizumab in treating Type 1 Diabetes is significant =
for two reasons. First, over a year=E2=80=99s long study the treatment was =
shown to delay the onset of T1D symptoms by an average of five years. For p=
atients like Mikayla (profiled in the Nature piece) it=E2=80=99s delayed he=
r need for insulin therapy for 6.5 years (and counting). Second, Teplizumab=
 is the first drug of its kind to delay the onset of any autoimmune disease=
, such as rheumatoid arthritis and multiple sclerosis.
Teplizumab is an antibody therapy, that blocks T-Cells from destroying insu=
lin-producing islet cells in the pancreas. There=E2=80=99s been a recent wa=
ve of advancement in T-Cell therapies, which prompted this tweet from Not B=
oring=E2=80=99s own Elliot Hershberg:=20
(3) Blood test for early Alzheimer=E2=80=99s detection [ https://substack.c=
om/redirect/137fc7f7-fbc6-4e11-b1a1-c927919c392d?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8=
J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
From the NIH
These results suggest that SOBA could detect toxic oligomers in the blood e=
ven before cognitive impairment occurs. It could thus form the basis for ea=
rly diagnostic tests of Alzheimer=E2=80=99s disease and other neurodegenera=
tive diseases.
This study was published back in December =E2=80=9822, but for whatever rea=
son was trending on Hacker News this week, and given its significance we th=
ought we=E2=80=99d re-surface it. A new test, which is not yet widely avail=
able, is able to detect the early biological signs of Alzhiemer=E2=80=99s d=
isease. Alzheimer=E2=80=99s disease involves formation of toxic aggregates,=
 called oligomers, which start to form 10-20 years prior to the onset of Al=
zheimer=E2=80=99s symptoms. The new test, called SOBA, can detect these oli=
gomers early and allows for intervention prior to Alzheimer=E2=80=99s causi=
ng irreparable brain damage.
Variants of the SOBA test may also be able to identify oligomers associated=
 with other neurodegenerative diseases, such as Parkinson=E2=80=99s, well b=
efore signs of cognitive impairment. Early detection FTW.
(4) Binge Drinking May Be Curbed With a Pill [ https://substack.com/redirec=
t/24771897-a7aa-4294-ae65-165e3429cff7?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_Zl=
NuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Ted Alcorn [ https://substack.com/redirect/dbbecdac-c6db-41de-9f63-64a9ace7=
aa93?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] f=
or The New York Times
By the end of the 12-week study, those given naltrexone reported bingeing l=
ess frequently and consuming less alcohol than those who had been given a p=
lacebo, a change that lasted for up to six months. The most commonly report=
ed side effect of naltrexone was nausea, although it was generally mild and=
 resolved itself as people adjusted to taking the drug.
The pace at which new therapies, treatments, and drugs are being introduced=
 is quite dizzying. But sometimes, advancement is merely a matter of repurp=
osing existing treatments for new use cases. One example here is semagltude=
, a drug traditionally used to treat diabetes that is now being repurposed =
as a highly effective weight-loss treatment. Another example is naltrexone.=
=20
The drug has been used for decades in treating patients with severe alcohol=
 disorders. Now, a new study finds that it may also be effective (and feasi=
ble) for more casual binge-drinkers. =E2=80=9CCasual binge-drinker=E2=80=9D=
 seems like an oxymoron, but nearly half of American drinkers report =E2=80=
=9Cbinging=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94 defined as four drink for males and three dri=
nks for females in one setting. If occasionally drinking four+ drinks durin=
g a single sitting is cool, then consider me Miles Davis=E2=80=A6or somethi=
ng.=20
The double-blind study, which tracked 120 men, found that taking naltrexone=
 prior to drinking resulted in less frequent binging and less alcohol consu=
mption. The most common side effect was nausea, but that generally subsided=
 as the participants=E2=80=99 bodies acclimated to the drug.
If you=E2=80=99re one of those =E2=80=9Ccasual binge-drinkers,=E2=80=9D it =
may be worth asking your healthcare provider if naltrexone is right for you=
=2E And at the very least, mix in a water.=20
